1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:26,020
 [ Music ]

2
00:00:26,020 --> 00:00:27,860
 >> Good morning, church.

3
00:00:27,860 --> 00:00:28,760
 >> Good morning.

4
00:00:28,760 --> 00:00:30,360
 Good morning, indeed.

5
00:00:30,360 --> 00:00:32,360
 Our sermon series is called Make Room.

6
00:00:32,360 --> 00:00:34,840
 There's a very crowded -- we have a lot of people in here today.

7
00:00:34,840 --> 00:00:38,640
 So if there is room next to you to make some room, could you let us know?

8
00:00:38,640 --> 00:00:42,380
 So if you're sitting in the back, there might be some seats down front.

9
00:00:42,380 --> 00:00:43,840
 You can come and join us.

10
00:00:43,840 --> 00:00:45,180
 Come on, come on, come on.

11
00:00:45,180 --> 00:00:48,380
 Yes. Let's make room for each other.

12
00:00:48,380 --> 00:00:48,880
 All right.

13
00:00:48,880 --> 00:00:50,220
 Well, good morning.

14
00:00:50,220 --> 00:00:53,320
 If you're joining us online, a very good morning to you as well.

15
00:00:53,320 --> 00:00:57,020
 Okay. I'm going to start today with a little Cantonese lesson.

16
00:00:57,020 --> 00:00:59,000
 So if you know Cantonese already, that's great.

17
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:00,660
 If you're local Hong Konger.

18
00:01:00,660 --> 00:01:04,800
 But if you don't, okay, this is a little saying for you today, okay?

19
00:01:04,800 --> 00:01:06,100
 It goes like this.

20
00:01:06,100 --> 00:01:09,400
 [ Foreign Language ]

21
00:01:09,400 --> 00:01:14,940
 Okay? Now, as with many Cantonese idioms and sayings, right,

22
00:01:14,940 --> 00:01:19,380
 the direct translation into English doesn't really make much sense, right?

23
00:01:19,380 --> 00:01:22,980
 If you directly translate this phrase, it sounds something like,

24
00:01:22,980 --> 00:01:26,720
 "Why would there be such a big toad jumping around on the street?"

25
00:01:26,720 --> 00:01:28,620
 Okay? Like, it doesn't make sense, right?

26
00:01:28,620 --> 00:01:31,020
 Toads jumping around on the street.

27
00:01:31,020 --> 00:01:35,160
 But the meaning behind it, it's something more along the lines of,

28
00:01:35,160 --> 00:01:37,500
 "It's too good to be true," right?

29
00:01:37,500 --> 00:01:39,440
 There's no such thing as a free lunch.

30
00:01:39,440 --> 00:01:43,400
 Apparently, maybe once upon a time, big toads were very desirable, okay,

31
00:01:43,400 --> 00:01:44,560
 for food or whatever.

32
00:01:44,560 --> 00:01:45,680
 So, you know, right?

33
00:01:45,680 --> 00:01:47,440
 It's too good to be true, right?

34
00:01:47,440 --> 00:01:48,240
 It can't be true.

35
00:01:48,240 --> 00:01:49,600
 It's too wonderful.

36
00:01:49,600 --> 00:01:52,040
 It's too good.

37
00:01:52,040 --> 00:01:55,080
 And maybe, you know, you've heard news like that, you know, like,

38
00:01:55,080 --> 00:01:58,980
 when you hear news that sounds too good to be true at first, right,

39
00:01:58,980 --> 00:02:02,220
 our initial reaction usually is doubt, right?

40
00:02:02,220 --> 00:02:03,620
 We think, "That doesn't happen."

41
00:02:03,620 --> 00:02:06,220
 No, that's not really going to happen.

42
00:02:06,220 --> 00:02:09,820
 My biggest doubt in life is getting free upgrades, right,

43
00:02:09,820 --> 00:02:12,060
 when I travel, when I fly, okay?

44
00:02:12,060 --> 00:02:15,940
 You know, I'm always hoping and praying, "Lord, for that free upgrade," right?

45
00:02:15,940 --> 00:02:17,000
 I do all the tactics.

46
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:19,680
 Sometimes I dress up a little bit nicer, okay?

47
00:02:19,680 --> 00:02:22,940
 And then you're really kind to the person at the check-in desk, "Oh, wow,

48
00:02:22,940 --> 00:02:25,980
 you look lovely today," you know, it's like, "Thank you for, you know,

49
00:02:25,980 --> 00:02:28,100
 being so patient with us," you know, like, okay.

50
00:02:28,100 --> 00:02:30,620
 And then, you know, so at the end, you know, as they're about to, you know,

51
00:02:30,620 --> 00:02:33,580
 put in, it's like, "Is there any chance of an upgrade today?"

52
00:02:33,580 --> 00:02:35,860
 You know, just asking, just wondering, right?

53
00:02:35,860 --> 00:02:40,020
 The answer has always, always been no, okay?

54
00:02:40,020 --> 00:02:41,460
 But I hear people's stories, right?

55
00:02:41,460 --> 00:02:44,100
 Then they're like 45 minutes late to check in, right?

56
00:02:44,100 --> 00:02:46,820
 They're all frazzled, you know, their luggage is everywhere, you know,

57
00:02:46,820 --> 00:02:48,380
 they don't have their passports on them.

58
00:02:48,380 --> 00:02:52,080
 And the end, the check-in person is like, "Oh, you look really stressed out.

59
00:02:52,080 --> 00:02:56,000
 Why don't I upgrade you so you can relax a little bit," right?

60
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:00,520
 Actually, this happened before me in front of my very eyes one time.

61
00:03:00,520 --> 00:03:04,840
 So a few years ago, my wife and I had just been on a...we were on a mission trip,

62
00:03:04,840 --> 00:03:06,840
 okay, doing the Lord's work, okay?

63
00:03:06,840 --> 00:03:10,280
 And it was hot and sweaty, it was a really tough trip.

64
00:03:10,280 --> 00:03:12,720
 And we were coming home from Hong Kong, okay?

65
00:03:12,720 --> 00:03:17,280
 So as we were checking in to come home, I was in charge of...I don't know why I was

66
00:03:17,280 --> 00:03:20,780
 put in charge, worst person ever to put in charge, anything administrative, right,

67
00:03:20,780 --> 00:03:21,340
 Dewey?

68
00:03:21,340 --> 00:03:22,260
 Do not trust me with it.

69
00:03:22,260 --> 00:03:23,820
 But at that moment, they did.

70
00:03:23,820 --> 00:03:26,460
 And I was distributing out the boarding passes.

71
00:03:26,460 --> 00:03:33,340
 And I noticed everyone's number was super low, right, like single digits, 1B, 3A, 6D,

72
00:03:33,340 --> 00:03:34,140
 stuff like that, right?

73
00:03:34,140 --> 00:03:38,140
 It's like, "Oh, okay, I think we got upgraded, apart from mine, okay?

74
00:03:38,140 --> 00:03:41,420
 I was in 11B, okay, 11B."

75
00:03:41,420 --> 00:03:44,620
 So, you know, I was handing out the boarding passes and then I said to my wife,

76
00:03:44,620 --> 00:03:49,680
 you know, "I think everyone in the group, in the team got upgraded apart from me."

77
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:50,840
 She said, "Oh, no, surely not.

78
00:03:50,840 --> 00:03:52,920
 You know, they checked us in together, you'll be fine."

79
00:03:52,920 --> 00:03:56,240
 And then she said this, right, "Even if that happens, right,

80
00:03:56,240 --> 00:03:57,880
 I'll come sit with you instead."

81
00:03:57,880 --> 00:03:59,200
 It's like, "Oh, so sweet."

82
00:03:59,200 --> 00:04:01,400
 Well, we were newlywed at that time, okay?

83
00:04:01,400 --> 00:04:02,120
 So...

84
00:04:02,120 --> 00:04:06,080
 And so we get on the plane, right?

85
00:04:06,080 --> 00:04:10,280
 And sure enough, okay, as we're going on, they were like, "Okay, Mr. Bennett,

86
00:04:10,280 --> 00:04:11,640
 yes, to the left, right?

87
00:04:11,640 --> 00:04:13,640
 Oh, Mr. Tsang, to the left."

88
00:04:13,640 --> 00:04:17,660
 Now, to the left is a good thing in planes, not in Beyonce songs, right?

89
00:04:17,660 --> 00:04:21,140
 But on the airplane, okay, to the left is a good thing because that's where the

90
00:04:21,140 --> 00:04:24,140
 upper classes are, right, the upper cabin classes, right?

91
00:04:24,140 --> 00:04:27,220
 And so, you know, they all went to the left and sure enough, when they got to me,

92
00:04:27,220 --> 00:04:29,980
 they're like, "Okay, sir, you sit right here."

93
00:04:29,980 --> 00:04:33,180
 Okay, I was in the very first row of the business class, right,

94
00:04:33,180 --> 00:04:40,340
 next to the toilet and the curtain, okay, with a screaming child next to me, right?

95
00:04:40,340 --> 00:04:41,420
 You say, "What happened to my wife?"

96
00:04:41,420 --> 00:04:42,940
 Okay, she dropped me like a bad habit.

97
00:04:42,940 --> 00:04:46,320
 The moment she went left and they handed her a cocktail, I was like, "Oh,

98
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:49,560
 Mrs. Tsang, here's a mango cocktail," or whatever it was, and she forgot

99
00:04:49,560 --> 00:04:51,520
 about me totally, okay?

100
00:04:51,520 --> 00:04:52,160
 Gone.

101
00:04:52,160 --> 00:04:56,400
 I didn't see her for the rest of the flight, okay?

102
00:04:56,400 --> 00:04:58,800
 You know, and so, you know, this is why, you know, like, I doubt, right?

103
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:01,240
 Do good things really happen?

104
00:05:01,240 --> 00:05:03,520
 Maybe not, okay?

105
00:05:03,520 --> 00:05:08,320
 Now, it's just a funny illustration to start my point, but doubt is this thing,

106
00:05:08,320 --> 00:05:08,600
 right?

107
00:05:08,620 --> 00:05:13,020
 Doubt is a very natural part of our humanity, right?

108
00:05:13,020 --> 00:05:16,060
 And in some ways, doubt is a good thing, right?

109
00:05:16,060 --> 00:05:21,180
 We can't just believe what everyone says all the time, right?

110
00:05:21,180 --> 00:05:24,180
 When we hear lies, when we hear things that are not true,

111
00:05:24,180 --> 00:05:29,860
 when we see misrepresentations of facts and reality, not only should we doubt

112
00:05:29,860 --> 00:05:34,100
 these things, but our doubt actually gives us a voice to speak out, right,

113
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:38,880
 and shed light into injustice, and darkness, and untruths that are being

114
00:05:38,880 --> 00:05:41,960
 happened around us.

115
00:05:41,960 --> 00:05:48,360
 But what happens when our doubt begins to enter our relationship with God?

116
00:05:48,360 --> 00:05:51,520
 And this might be something we all struggle with too.

117
00:05:51,520 --> 00:05:56,600
 At some point in our walk with Jesus, we have doubted His goodness,

118
00:05:56,600 --> 00:06:03,680
 we have doubted His love, we have doubted His power, and how He can relate to us,

119
00:06:03,680 --> 00:06:08,260
 right, especially when we see tragedies unfold before us as we've seen in our

120
00:06:08,260 --> 00:06:09,960
 city.

121
00:06:09,960 --> 00:06:12,960
 It only makes sense that we ask ourselves the question, right,

122
00:06:12,960 --> 00:06:15,680
 "Where is God in all of this?

123
00:06:15,680 --> 00:06:22,380
 How could such a loving, powerful God allow for something like this to happen?"

124
00:06:22,380 --> 00:06:26,200
 Right, these are questions, very real questions we as a whole city are

125
00:06:26,200 --> 00:06:29,160
 wrestling with right now.

126
00:06:29,160 --> 00:06:34,080
 Right, two weeks ago during the fire, I'm sure I and many of you prayed, right?

127
00:06:34,080 --> 00:06:37,560
 I remember specifically praying for act of God.

128
00:06:37,560 --> 00:06:41,880
 I remember praying, "God, just...I know it's the driest day of the year so far

129
00:06:41,880 --> 00:06:45,560
 right now, but just somehow form a rain cloud over the buildings right now and

130
00:06:45,560 --> 00:06:49,240
 just pour down your rain on it so we can put out these fires and we can see lives

131
00:06:49,240 --> 00:06:51,280
 get saved."

132
00:06:51,280 --> 00:06:53,720
 But that didn't happen.

133
00:06:53,720 --> 00:06:59,120
 Right, and here, two weeks, three weeks later, we're sifting through the damage.

134
00:06:59,120 --> 00:07:05,160
 Reeling in the pain and grief and mourning of what's happened in our city.

135
00:07:05,160 --> 00:07:11,240
 And when we sit in the aftermath of a tragedy, of a disaster,

136
00:07:11,240 --> 00:07:14,840
 it's very easy for doubt to set in.

137
00:07:14,840 --> 00:07:20,280
 So the question we want to answer today is this, how do we deal with doubt?

138
00:07:20,280 --> 00:07:25,640
 Because when it's unresolved, doubt can drive us to a place of despair

139
00:07:25,640 --> 00:07:27,520
 and hopelessness.

140
00:07:27,520 --> 00:07:33,520
 When we give in to doubt, it drives a wedge between us and God.

141
00:07:33,520 --> 00:07:38,440
 When we begin to doubt God's love for us, so we no longer want to draw near to Him.

142
00:07:38,440 --> 00:07:42,600
 We begin to doubt God's plan for us and purposes for us, so we don't trust Him

143
00:07:42,600 --> 00:07:43,720
 anymore.

144
00:07:43,720 --> 00:07:49,000
 When we begin to question God's goodness and kindness, we close our hearts and leave

145
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:53,480
 no room for Him to do His work in our lives.

146
00:07:53,480 --> 00:07:55,320
 And actually, the enemy knows this well.

147
00:07:55,320 --> 00:08:02,880
 Doubt is one of the first things the enemy uses to put distance between us and God.

148
00:08:02,880 --> 00:08:07,080
 Right at the very beginning, that was his strategy, to make Eve doubt the goodness

149
00:08:07,080 --> 00:08:12,200
 of God and cause her to sin by trusting herself instead of trusting what God

150
00:08:12,200 --> 00:08:15,320
 had told her.

151
00:08:15,320 --> 00:08:19,560
 Eve begins to put doubt on the throne of her heart instead of God.

152
00:08:19,560 --> 00:08:25,800
 He comes to her with these tricky questions, saying stuff like, "Did God really say you

153
00:08:25,800 --> 00:08:29,800
 must not eat from any tree in the garden?

154
00:08:29,800 --> 00:08:31,360
 You will not surely die.

155
00:08:31,360 --> 00:08:33,960
 Come on, Eve, just think about it for a minute, right?

156
00:08:33,960 --> 00:08:36,280
 Maybe what God's saying is not true.

157
00:08:36,280 --> 00:08:39,960
 Maybe you should trust in yourself."

158
00:08:39,960 --> 00:08:44,720
 And it was these lies of the Satan, these lies of the enemy that caused humanity to

159
00:08:44,720 --> 00:08:48,840
 doubt God's commands, His ways, His love.

160
00:08:48,840 --> 00:08:55,200
 And the consequence of that was sin entering into the world.

161
00:08:55,200 --> 00:09:01,080
 When doubt sits on the throne of our hearts, it blinds us to the goodness of God.

162
00:09:01,080 --> 00:09:06,280
 And what we want to do is to take doubt off the throne and wrestle with it head

163
00:09:06,280 --> 00:09:13,800
 on because actually, if we take doubt and use it in the correct way, it can actually

164
00:09:13,800 --> 00:09:16,520
 be used for good.

165
00:09:16,520 --> 00:09:21,160
 And I think it's that through doubt that we can better understand the realities of

166
00:09:21,160 --> 00:09:28,560
 sin and brokenness in this world and in our lives and draw us closer to God,

167
00:09:28,560 --> 00:09:32,120
 draw us closer to the truth.

168
00:09:32,120 --> 00:09:37,640
 The late leader and pastor, Tim Keller, says it this way, "A faith without some

169
00:09:37,640 --> 00:09:41,720
 doubt is like a human body without any antibodies.

170
00:09:41,720 --> 00:09:45,640
 People who blithely go through life, too busy or indifferent, to ask hard

171
00:09:45,640 --> 00:09:51,160
 questions about why they believe as they do will find themselves defenseless against

172
00:09:51,160 --> 00:09:55,560
 either the experience of tragedy or the questions of skeptics.

173
00:09:55,560 --> 00:10:02,280
 Believers should acknowledge and wrestle with doubts because this is the kind of

174
00:10:02,280 --> 00:10:07,680
 doubt that helps us see that even through things we might not understand,

175
00:10:07,680 --> 00:10:10,560
 God is still in control.

176
00:10:10,560 --> 00:10:12,480
 He knows what He's doing.

177
00:10:12,480 --> 00:10:13,440
 He still cares.

178
00:10:13,440 --> 00:10:14,400
 He still loves.

179
00:10:14,400 --> 00:10:19,120
 And even though we might doubt it at times, the truth is that with God,

180
00:10:19,120 --> 00:10:23,120
 all things are still possible."

181
00:10:23,120 --> 00:10:27,840
 And so, as we step into week two of Advent and look at the person of Zechariah,

182
00:10:27,840 --> 00:10:31,160
 this is the story we see being played out.

183
00:10:31,160 --> 00:10:37,240
 A faithful man of God wrestling with doubt, holding on in the end to God's promises

184
00:10:37,240 --> 00:10:40,280
 until they come through in the end.

185
00:10:40,280 --> 00:10:43,560
 So, let's turn to the scriptures and see what it says.

186
00:10:43,560 --> 00:10:47,400
 We're in the book of Luke, as the lady so beautifully read just now,

187
00:10:47,400 --> 00:10:50,440
 chapter 1, verse 5.

188
00:10:50,440 --> 00:10:57,360
 It says this, "In the time of Herod, king of Judea, there was a priest named

189
00:10:57,360 --> 00:11:01,880
 Zechariah who belonged to the priestly division of Abijah.

190
00:11:01,880 --> 00:11:05,400
 His wife Elizabeth was also a descendant of Aaron.

191
00:11:05,400 --> 00:11:09,680
 Both of them were righteous in the sight of God, observing all the Lord's commands

192
00:11:09,680 --> 00:11:11,640
 and decreased blamelessly.

193
00:11:11,640 --> 00:11:17,000
 But they were childless because Elizabeth was not able to conceive,

194
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:20,920
 and they were both very old."

195
00:11:20,920 --> 00:11:25,840
 So, Luke describes what the very first Christmas was like.

196
00:11:25,840 --> 00:11:29,800
 He starts his gospel by describing to us the very first Christmas.

197
00:11:29,800 --> 00:11:35,480
 Now, in our modern portrayal of Christmas, right, it's always very festive.

198
00:11:35,480 --> 00:11:37,160
 It looks very warm and inviting.

199
00:11:37,160 --> 00:11:38,120
 We look around us, right?

200
00:11:38,120 --> 00:11:42,480
 The team have done a beautiful job decorating the whole building, right?

201
00:11:42,480 --> 00:11:44,720
 Today, we have the market outside.

202
00:11:44,720 --> 00:11:46,160
 It's very warm and inviting.

203
00:11:46,160 --> 00:11:47,000
 We have the bake sale.

204
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:49,800
 We have mulled wine next week, all this kind of stuff, right?

205
00:11:49,800 --> 00:11:53,480
 You go down to the malls, IFC, Pacific Place, it's all like that, right?

206
00:11:53,480 --> 00:11:59,040
 Trees, decorations, cookies, mulled wine, turkey, you know, kisses under the mistletoe,

207
00:11:59,040 --> 00:12:01,920
 all this really lovely stuff, right?

208
00:12:01,920 --> 00:12:06,360
 And so, it's easy for us to think that Christmas is always associated with,

209
00:12:06,360 --> 00:12:10,400
 like, warm, fuzzy, jolly things.

210
00:12:10,400 --> 00:12:15,960
 But we're reminded in the gospels that the first Christmas was far from this.

211
00:12:15,960 --> 00:12:20,680
 And in fact, God's plan of redemption when Jesus first came into the world starts

212
00:12:20,680 --> 00:12:27,720
 with a backdrop of doubt, of pain, of the people crying out for rescue, right?

213
00:12:27,720 --> 00:12:34,800
 For over 400 years, the Israelites were crying out to the Lord, crying out for rescue,

214
00:12:34,800 --> 00:12:40,040
 waiting for this so-called promised Messiah to come and rescue them

215
00:12:40,040 --> 00:12:41,760
 from the oppressors.

216
00:12:41,760 --> 00:12:44,640
 But things just go from bad to worse, right?

217
00:12:44,640 --> 00:12:48,320
 They start with the Assyrians, and it goes on to the Babylonians, and the Persians,

218
00:12:48,320 --> 00:12:50,520
 and the Greeks, and now the Romans.

219
00:12:50,520 --> 00:12:58,440
 All these foreign forces have been ruling over their country.

220
00:12:58,440 --> 00:13:02,640
 And they've been waiting for someone to come and restore the kingdom.

221
00:13:02,640 --> 00:13:07,280
 But instead, at the turn of time and time again, instead of rescue,

222
00:13:07,280 --> 00:13:10,600
 just comes more oppression.

223
00:13:10,600 --> 00:13:14,200
 And as Andrew pointed out to us last week, this latest ruler they have in this little

224
00:13:14,200 --> 00:13:17,760
 place in Judea was a man called Herod, right?

225
00:13:17,760 --> 00:13:20,440
 A self-proclaimed king of the Jews, right?

226
00:13:20,440 --> 00:13:27,640
 A cruel man who seemed to have no problem ordering the execution of innocent babies.

227
00:13:27,640 --> 00:13:30,680
 Now, that doesn't make for good decorations.

228
00:13:30,680 --> 00:13:34,560
 Could you imagine Pacific Place right now doing a "Meet King Herod" instead of "Meet

229
00:13:34,560 --> 00:13:36,240
 Father Christmas," okay?

230
00:13:36,240 --> 00:13:39,920
 Hong Kong's mom Facebook group would go absolutely crazy, right?

231
00:13:39,920 --> 00:13:40,960
 That's not the kind of stuff.

232
00:13:40,960 --> 00:13:41,760
 It's not inviting.

233
00:13:41,760 --> 00:13:42,960
 It's not warm, right?

234
00:13:42,960 --> 00:13:43,720
 It's dark.

235
00:13:43,720 --> 00:13:44,880
 It's real.

236
00:13:44,880 --> 00:13:51,800
 It deals with some of the really bad things that are happening around us.

